          <!-- Paper 6 -->
      <div class="paper">
        <h2>A Cost-Effective Dedicated Cooperative Blockchain
 for Verifying Certificate Issuers and Certificates</h2>
        <p class="authors"><strong> Ankit K C</strong>, Deepesh Bhandari, Rojalina Priyadarshini, Pramod Kumar Meher </p>
        <p class="venue">In Review </p>
         <div class="paper-links">
      <button class="btn-sm toggle-btn" data-target="abstract-6">Read Abstract</button>
      <button class="btn-sm toggle-btn" data-target="doi-6">Preprint</button>

    </div>
      <!-- Hidden Sections -->
      <div id="abstract-6" class="paper-content hidden">
        <p>
          Certificate fraud is a critical issue in educational and professional sectors, often resulting in the hiring of unqualified individuals and compromising organizational efficiency. While blockchain-based solutions for certificate management have been proposed, they often encounter challenges such as limited scalability, high transaction costs, and integration difficulties with existing institutional systems. This paper introduces a scalable cooperative blockchain framework designed for secure and verifiable certificate storage. Unlike traditional public or consortium blockchains, the proposed framework utilizes decentralized governance with equal institutional participation and employs dynamically adjustable block sizes to optimize both storage and performance. Certificates are stored off-chain,
 with only their cryptographic hashes and student id maintained on the blockchain, ensuring immutability and authenticity. By integrating with existing databases, the system minimizes storage overhead and transaction fees. The implementation of the proposed framework is done, and a comparison with Ethereum and Hyperledger Fabric demonstrates its efficiency, particularly in reducing storage requirements. Simulations demonstrate the framework’s capacity to manage large-scale, dynamic certificate issuance efficiently, making it particularly suitable for
 academic institutions. Additionally, the framework has broader applications for verifying professional certifications, securing public records, and authenticating employment credentials. These simulations confirm the robustness of the cooperative blockchain framework and its potential to significantly reduce certificate fraud across multiple sectors.</p>
      </div>
